1. Importing libraries and loading data¶

These libraries are used for data handling (pandas, numpy), visualization (matplotlib, seaborn, plotly, missingno), and machine learning tasks (scikit-learn). They help in preprocessing, model building, evaluation, and optimization, making data analysis and predictive modeling efficient.

In [134]:
# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd  # For data manipulation and analysis
import numpy as np  # For numerical computations
import missingno as msno  # For visualizing missing values
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # For static data visualization
import seaborn as sns  # For enhanced data visualization

# Import Plotly for interactive visualizations
import plotly.express as px
import plotly.graph_objects as go
from plotly.subplots import make_subplots

# Suppress warnings to keep the output clean
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

# Import preprocessing modules from scikit-learn
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler  # For feature scaling
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder  # For encoding categorical variables

# Import machine learning models
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier  # Decision Tree model
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier  # Random Forest model
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB  # Naive Bayes classifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier  # K-Nearest Neighbors classifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression  # Logistic Regression model

# Import tools for splitting data and model evaluation
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split  # Splitting dataset into train and test sets
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score  # For measuring model accuracy
from sklearn import metrics  # Various performance metrics
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve  # Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score, confusion_matrix, precision_score, f1_score, accuracy_score, classification_report, roc_auc_score  # Additional model evaluation metrics

# Import GridSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

The heatmap visually represents the correlation between numerical features in the dataset.

In [141]:
# Correlation Heatmap (For numeric features)
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(numeric_df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.title('Correlation Matrix')
plt.show()

Correlation values range from -1 to 1.High correlation (greater than 0.8 or less than -0.8) suggests that two features provide similar information, making one redundant.When two features are highly correlated, keeping both may lead to multicollinearity, which can negatively impact model performance. To improve efficiency, one of the correlated features can be removed. Here TotalCharges and MonthlyCharges show a strong correlation, keeping only one may be preferable to reduce redundancy.

3.Data Visualization¶

With below two donut-style pie charts we can visualize gender and churn distributions and also it customizes labels, percentages, and annotations to enhance readability, making it easier to compare gender proportions and churn rates side by side.From the below data we can easy see that 26.6% of customers have churned and switched to another provider and the customer base consists of 49.5% females and 50.5% males.

In [152]:
# Define labels for gender and churn categories
g_labels = ['Male', 'Female']
c_labels = ['No', 'Yes']

# Define custom colors
gender_colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e']  # Blue for Male, Orange for Female
churn_colors = ['#2ca02c', '#d62728']  # Green for No, Red for Yes

# Create subplots with 'domain' type for pie charts
fig = make_subplots(rows=1, cols=2, specs=[[{'type':'domain'}, {'type':'domain'}]])

# Add pie chart for Gender distribution with custom colors
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=g_labels, values=df['gender'].value_counts(), name="Gender",
                     marker=dict(colors=gender_colors)), 1, 1)

# Add pie chart for Churn distribution with custom colors
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=c_labels, values=df['Churn'].value_counts(), name="Churn",
                     marker=dict(colors=churn_colors)), 1, 2)

# Customize the pie charts to have a donut-like appearance
fig.update_traces(hole=.4, hoverinfo="label+percent+name", textfont_size=16)

# Update layout with title and annotations for clarity
fig.update_layout(
    title_text="Gender and Churn Distributions",
    # Add labels in the center of the donut charts
    annotations=[dict(text='Gender', x=0.16, y=0.5, font_size=20, showarrow=False),
                 dict(text='Churn', x=0.84, y=0.5, font_size=20, showarrow=False)]
)

# Display the pie charts
fig.show()

Create a donut chart visualizing churn distribution (Yes/No) and overlays a second pie chart showing gender distribution within each churn category.Data shows that there is negligible difference in the percentage or count of customers who switched service providers, as both genders exhibited similar behavior when migrating to another provider or firm.

In [155]:
# Define main pie chart data
labels = ["Churn: Yes", "Churn: No"]
values = [1869, 5163]
colors = ['#FF6347', '#4682B4']  # Tomato & Steel Blue
explode = (0.1, 0.1)  # Highlight both sections

# Define gender-based sub-chart data
labels_gender = ["F", "M", "F", "M"]
sizes_gender = [939, 930, 2544, 2619]
colors_gender = ['#FFB6C1', '#87CEFA', '#FF69B4', '#1E90FF']  # Light Pink, Light Blue, Hot Pink, Dodger Blue
explode_gender = (0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05)

# Configure figure
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
textprops = {"fontsize": 14}

# Main Pie Chart (Churn Yes/No)
plt.pie(values, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', pctdistance=1.15,
        labeldistance=1.05, colors=colors, startangle=160,
        frame=True, explode=explode, radius=10, textprops=textprops, counterclock=True)

# Inner Pie Chart (Gender Distribution)
plt.pie(sizes_gender, labels=labels_gender, colors=colors_gender,
        startangle=160, explode=explode_gender, radius=7,
        labeldistance=0.7, textprops=textprops, counterclock=True)

# Draw center circle to make it a donut chart
centre_circle = plt.Circle((0, 0), 4.5, color='black', fc='white', linewidth=0)
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.gca().add_artist(centre_circle)

# Add title
plt.title('Churn Distribution by Gender (Male: M, Female: F)', fontsize=15, y=1.05)

# Final plot adjustments
plt.axis('equal')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Data Preprocessing¶

Function converts categorical (object) data into numerical labels using Label Encoding. It ensures that only columns with an 'object' dtype are transformed, making them suitable for machine learning models

In [173]:
def object_to_int(dataframe_series):
    """
    Converts categorical (object) data into numerical values using Label Encoding.

    Parameters:
    dataframe_series (pd.Series): A column from a pandas DataFrame.

    Returns:
    pd.Series: Transformed series with integer labels if the data type is 'object'.
    """
    # Check if the column is of type 'object' (categorical)
    if dataframe_series.dtype == 'object':
        # Apply Label Encoding to convert categories into numeric values
        dataframe_series = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(dataframe_series)

    return dataframe_series

# Apply the object_to_int function to all columns in the DataFrame
df = df.apply(lambda x: object_to_int(x))

def distplot(feature, frame, color='#1E90FF'):  # Using Dodger Blue for better visibility
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 3))
    plt.title(f"Distribution for {feature}")

    # Improved distribution plot with modern Seaborn function
    sns.histplot(frame[feature], kde=True, color=color, bins=30)  # Histogram with KDE overlay

    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel("Density")
    plt.show()
# List of numerical columns to visualize
num_cols = ["tenure", "MonthlyCharges", "TotalCharges"]

# Loop through each numerical feature and plot its distribution
for feat in num_cols:
    distplot(feat, df)  # Call the distplot function for each column

Categorize features into three groups: numerical columns for standardization, categorical columns for one-hot encoding (cat_cols_ohe), and categorical columns for label encoding (cat_cols_le). This ensures appropriate preprocessing for each data type, improving model performance and standardizes numerical features using StandardScaler, ensuring they have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. The scaler is fitted on X_train and then applied to both X_train and X_test, preventing data leakage

In [176]:
# Columns that require **One-Hot Encoding** (categorical variables with multiple distinct categories)
cat_cols_ohe = ['PaymentMethod', 'Contract', 'InternetService']

# Columns that require **Label Encoding** (categorical variables with binary or ordinal values)
# This is determined by subtracting numerical and one-hot encoded columns from the total feature set
cat_cols_le = list(set(X_train.columns) - set(num_cols) - set(cat_cols_ohe))

# Initialize the StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Apply Standardization (Z-score normalization) on numerical columns
# Fit and transform on training data
X_train[num_cols] = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[num_cols])

# Transform test data using the same scaler (without refitting)
X_test[num_cols] = scaler.transform(X_test[num_cols])

# Try different values of k
k_values = [3, 5, 7, 10, 15, 20]
accuracies = []

for k in k_values:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    accuracies.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

# Plot the accuracies for different k values

plt.plot(k_values, accuracies, marker='o', color='b')
plt.title('Effect of K on Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('K (Number of Neighbors)')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xticks(k_values)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
